<HEADLINE>
<P>
EMPIRE LEAGUE BASEBALL ROUNDUP; FLORES GETS COMPLETE GAME AS EL DORADO BEATS 
CYPRESS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JASON H. REID, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Benito Flores looked forward to the meeting for more than 10 months and he 
would not accept another loss. 
</P>
<P>
 So when things began unraveling around the El Dorado High pitcher against 
Cypress, Flores did what he promised himself he would: He took charge. 
</P>
<P>
 The senior left-hander worked out of a sixth-inning jam and pitched a complete 
game in leading El Dorado to a 4-1 victory in an Empire League baseball opener 
Friday at El Dorado. 
</P>
<P>
 Flores (2-1) pitched a five-hitter and struck out seven for El Dorado (6-2, 
1-0 in league play). 
</P>
<P>
 Pitching with a 4-0 lead entering the sixth, Flores gave up three hits and 
Cypress' only run when the Centurions' leadoff hitter, senior Ray Rios (three 
for three), scored on a one-out single by junior first baseman Brian Flanagan. 
Flanagan took second on a passed ball to give Cypress runners on second and 
third, but Flores ended the threat by striking out the next two batters. 
</P>
<P>
 The victory was especially gratifying for Flores and El Dorado because Cypress 
(4-3, 0-1) defeated El Dorado, 4-2, in the final game of the 1993 regular 
season, which kept the Golden Hawks out of the playoffs for only the third time 
in 13 seasons. 
</P>
<P>
 "I took it personal; we all did," Flores said. "We all thought about this game 
every time we went to practice." 
</P>
<P>
 Cypress senior right-hander Tim Larsen (1-2) was the winner in last season's 
showdown. Larsen pitched a complete game Friday, but he did not have his best 
stuff. 
</P>
<P>
 The first three hitters in the Golden Hawks' lineup (Ryan Reyes, Chris Beck 
and Jeff Moore) each were two for three. Beck, a junior third baseman, scored 
El Dorado's first run in the bottom of the first when senior right fielder 
Dante Spencer grounded out. 
</P>
<P>
 The Golden Hawks scored three runs in the third inning to take control. 
Moore's second home run of the season, which traveled approximately 360 feet 
and landed over the fence in right-center field, also drove in Beck. 
</P>
<P>
 In other league games: 
</P>
<P>
 Los Alamitos 5, Loara 3 (6, darkness) -- Myles Campbell struck out nine in 5 
1/3 innings for the visiting Griffins. Catcher Mark Ukleja hit a two-run homer 
in the third and Kevin Feterik went two for three with a double and a run 
scored for Los Alamitos (4-3, 1-0). Jeff Roncevich (1-2) took the loss for 
Loara (3-4, 0-1). 
</P>
<P>
 Katella 6, Esperanza 2 -- Jaret Wright pitched a three-hitter, striking out 
10, and homered for visiting Katella (3-3, 1-0). Esperanza is 3-4, 0-1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
