ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: NEWPORT BEACH; CITY TO HOLD ANNUAL LIFEGUARD TRYOUTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BOB ELSTON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The city will hold its annual lifeguard tryouts Sunday morning near the 
Newport Pier. 
</P>
<P>
 The rigorous test of physical stamina and swimming strength, plus a written 
quiz, will help officials in hiring 10 to 20 people for the summer lifeguard 
staff. 
</P>
<P>
 "We do one (test) every spring," said Lt. Jim Turner of the Newport Beach 
Marine Safety Division. "We are looking for the local aquatics athletes . . . 
from local high schools and colleges." 
</P>
<P>
 There will be an 800-yard swim, some running, and board paddling tests Sunday 
morning. 
</P>
<P>
 Applicants must turn 16 by July, 1994, and have good vision. The city hires 
both men and women for its lifeguard staff. 
</P>
<P>
 Turner said that it is getting increasingly difficult to find strong swimmers 
to fill the open positions. 
</P>
<P>
 "Our applications have been reasonably slim" this year, he said. "It just 
seems that there are fewer people out there swimming."BOB ELSTON 
</P>
