<P>
COLLEGE BASKETBALL / NCAA POSTSEASON TOURNAMENTS; WOMEN'S TOURNAMENT / MIDEAST 
REGIONAL; USC RETURNS TO ACTION IN CHASE FOR TITLE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By EARL GUSTKEY, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The USC women's basketball team, winner of five consecutive games since Coach 
Cheryl Miller predicted her team would not lose again this season, will play 
George Washington tonight at 7:30 in a second-round NCAA tournament game at the 
Sports Arena. 
</P>
<P>
 USC (24-3), ranked seventh in the final regular-season poll, meets the 
unranked Colonials (23-7) after defeating Portland, 77-62, on Thursday.George 
Washington, co-champion of the Atlantic 10 Conference, defeated Alabama 
Birmingham in its NCAA opener, 74-66. 
</P>
<P>
 With a victory tonight in senior All-American Lisa Leslie's final home game, 
the Trojans would advance to the Mideast Regional next week at the University 
of Arkansas.  
</P>
<P>
 Miller's team completed a 16-2 Pacific 10 championship season last weekend, 
but the Trojans have not played well in their last two, victories over Oregon 
State and Portland. 
</P>
<P>
 Generally, USC has lost much of the sizzle from its early- and midseason 
offense, and specifically its long-range shooting touch in recent outings. In 
practice this week, Miller has focused on shooting, lost timing and intensity.  
</P>
<P>
 George Washington lost to Rutgers in its conference tournament title game, 
79-71. Junior forward Darlene Saar is the Colonials' best player, averaging 
13.1 points and 8.8 rebounds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
